 that the question of aesthetic autonomy has ramifications that extend beyond art to encompass the nature of political transformation and forms of anticolonial resistance that challenge the Eurocentric concept of “Man,” upon which the aesthetic itself often depends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and societyxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt criticism. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aArt, ModernxPolitical aspects. 0aAutonomy (Psychology) in art. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSubjectivity in art. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024552?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024552/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles